The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
This is at least what the tourist guides tell you.
The building is riding between the ends of the platforms with a tower on each of its angles looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building was slightly decadent.
But once inside the ticket office from the roof to the roof, there is no doubt about the size of the company of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retardator to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this rail that was running to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond that which is today Saudi Arabia.
But the imperial ambitions of Germany drowned during the First World War.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
