The “Ape Car” to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accidents prevention technologies, Nissan has inspired itself, this time, to nature, and in particular to bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking for example the flying of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the four-zone Safety Shield produced by Nissan.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicle of the manufacturer's home.
During the flight, each apple creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to Nissan’s safety shield.
But the most important thing are the composite eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with an angle greater than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To re-create this visual feature, engineers have developed what they have called a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to a board microprocessor that immediately, enables to prevent collision.
“When it detects a barrier, the small robot imitates the movements of a bear and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels in a straight or greater corner to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not so, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bear, the robot cannot deviate up or down, and not even in diagonal; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can rotate and not exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act starting from these data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of the previous maneuver, for this it can work without interruptions and with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This can be surprising, but we’re not talking about gigabyte of memory, and not even about mega.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be serious in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the type with lithium ions.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to the destination by avoiding the obstacles on the route.
